segments.text: Dr. Mackin, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places of their birth if you remember them, the date and place of your birth, the schools you attended up to the time you entered college, whatever you can remember of your childhood life.
I was born in 1903 at Waxahachie, Texas, close to Dallas.
My mother was Willie Ina Hall Mackin and my father Alfred Cecil Mackin Sr.
My father died in my early childhood in about 1912.
He was a pianist and band director for the Village Band in Waxahachie and he was also, pretty interesting,
character in that he played the piano for the old silent movies.
You've heard of this.
This is one of my earliest remembrances in childhood.
I was listening to my father in the local theater playing for the Perils of Pauline or whatever it was.
I remember my father mostly for his piano.
playing, which has led me over the years to collect most of the world's records in piano music.
I have a big collection there.
My mother... Incidentally, my father was born in Illinois.
at the town of Gilman, just below Chicago, and he was one of the railroad Irish immigrants.
Of course, we believe that he descended from Brian Beru, as usual with Irishmen.
How close that is to the truth, I don't have any idea, you understand.
When my father died, we were...
Of course, pretty destitute, pretty close to destitute.
My mother became a schoolteacher.
We moved to Oklahoma, settled at Ada, excuse me, at Durant, Oklahoma first, and my mother taught for a while after going to the local teacher's college and getting
all the requirements off, she was there in the public schools for almost several years.
After that, she went to East Central State College at Ada, Oklahoma, and was a
critic teacher first in the model school, later professor of English, finally ended up as dean of women, so I got my academic side through my mother.
To come back
And to myself and my own schooling, I had some schooling at Waxahachie, I think up to about fourth grade or somewhere, fourth or fifth, I'm not sure of that.
And then some more of it in public schools and into the high school at Durant, Oklahoma.
I remember that I was in high school at the time the U.S. entered World War II.
One, excuse me.
That's 1917, I believe.
I went from there to the college, a two-year college, Southeastern State College now in Oklahoma.
Was there a year or something like that that I followed my mother to
to Ada.
She had already left before I left the college there.
I was actually working in the high school division of the college.
At that time, there were two years high school, two years college, and I was still working in the high school area at about that time.
And was that East Central State?
Was it Ada?
Yes, East Central State College at Ada.
At that time,
I had started into majoring in biology, by the way, at Southeastern in Durand, but when I moved to Ada, I found no satisfactory teacher there, so I shifted to industrial arts.
Played football and tennis.
This was the biggest part of my college career there.
19 and 22, prior to the time I graduated from college, I took my first teaching job at Tishomingo, Oklahoma.
Believe it or not, at 19 years old, I was principal of the high school, coach of athletics, taught all the industrial arts and whatever else was left over, including artistry.
That's how I got introduced to teaching.
It was quite a teaching load.
It was quite a teaching load.
How big a school was that?
A small town, Tishomingo, Oklahoma, not very far from College of Eden.
I spent that year, 22, 23, teaching there.
Then you interrupted your college education for a year.
Yes, I interrupted my college education for a year and then went back and swore I'd never teach another day.
I got back to East Central College and the president offered me a student job, a half-time job.
I got my bachelor's degree there in industrial arts and biology in 1924.
That's kind of an odd combination, isn't it?
No, it fits very well.
I'm still with both of them.
Well, I shouldn't say odd.
I guess maybe what I would change that to.
Well, unusual also sounds odd.
But I mean, I would say not very many people would put together biology and industrial arts, I would say.
I'm not sure that I did it intentionally.
I think it was just simply a matter of taking advantage of whatever opportunities came along.
to get what I wanted.
From what you said earlier, I would guess that biology was your first love.
Biology was the first love, but I lost that teacher.
But when I came back after teaching a year at Tishomingo, I found an excellent biology teacher had been hired by the college.
And, of course, I went right back to the biology end of it.
but I carried the other also because I did like it.
I didn't like the teaching.
I didn't like the industrial arts teaching, but I did like the biology.
One matter to back up just a little bit on your mother.
Was she a native Texan?
Yes, her people were farmers.
I know very little about them.
I never met my grandparents.
but my mother was adopted by a Waxahachie family and I knew this family and thought of her adopted parents as uncle and aunt.
He happened to be the sheriff of Ellis County at that time and was a
top man, lived in a big Victorian house, a real beautiful place.
So that was her upbringing.
Her family
Her mother and her father, I never knew because they died early apparently.
She was adopted by this, the Ryburn family, Jim Ryburn was the name.
You mentioned earlier that your last year of college you were doing some part-time teaching in the college.
Yes, it was an industrial arts and not in the college but in the model school attached to the college.
I had charge of the little rough ends and all of it.
Was the model school for a full
eleven years or twelve years, however many years they had in a public school?
Yes, it had at least two years of high school in it, and I was teaching high school grade students at that time.
Then you stayed on at the Central State for a good long while, didn't you?
Yes.
After I graduated, I was offered a job to teach biology and I became a full-time biology teacher first year of the graduate.
This was in, let's see, I got my bachelor's degree in 1924.
I taught the next year 24, 25 and 26, 27.
The following year I took leave of absence, went to the University of Illinois to study biology under Henry Baldwin Ward at Illinois.
It's the same man
Under him, Dr. Hopkins worked.
Did you choose Illinois because of Dr. Ward?
Yes, specifically because that was an area that I was interested in.
I chose, I chose him rather than the institution.
What was his area, you mean because of the area of biology he was in?
Yes, he was one of the famous parasitologists of the nation in those early days.
So I went to the University of Illinois.
I worked out a master's degree and eight hours of undergraduate work that the dean fined me in nine months and got a master's degree in
So that was a pretty busy year for you, I would imagine.
Nine months to take some undergraduate courses, plus enough for a master's.
The only thing that bothered me was this undergraduate work.
It was all in German.
Henry Baldwin was a product of the Prussian school of
of teachers, and he was a driver.
And he said, well, if you're going to have to take undergraduate work, do something that'll do you some good.
So he made me take German, which was about as rough as you would have picked.
It's pretty rough, yes.
I remember from the smattering of German I've had.
Did you then, after you received your master's, went back to Ada?
I returned to Ada and taught in the college.
At the time, I think I was an assistant professor.
In a couple of years, I was full professor.
I went back to the University of Illinois at Dr. Ward's invitation.
He gave me an assistantship.
in 1929, just in time for the stock crash, which helped me a great deal because I'd saved some money.
I mean, this money turned out to be twice as much under the Depression days as it would have been before.
So, to me, the Depression was
Just an episode that actually was a help in getting through.
I was there at Illinois working on my doctorate and took some marine work at the University of Washington Seattle in the summer and got my PhD in 1933.
Was that working under Dr. Ward?
Working under Dr. Ward.
I never found the course work difficult.
In fact, I don't think I made one B in all of the biological science that I took.
The main reason was that
In some areas, I was considerably better than my teachers because I'd had more field experience.
I admitted to the state of my boyhood, I spent mostly in the woods and fields and so on.
That was the thing that I did.
Especially when we were still back at Durant, we were
I spent nearly all of my time in the woods, and I knew a great deal about it.
Whether I had much reading there, I don't know.
When I went to the University of Illinois, I found most of the courses were fairly simple.
I didn't have much trouble.
Teaching at, in Ada, in East Central State, did you have to teach in the summers most of the time too?
Yes, I taught the entire year.
So you didn't have any summers off for research or anything like that?
No, but I did.
You understand that at that time, research was not looked upon with favor.
I did my research on my own, paid for it all, and I took trips every August.
I had a vacation in August after the summer term had been closed.
And I arranged over a good portion of the United States during those summer periods.
I was doing research back there at a time when the administration of the college just assumed I didn't do it.
How many hours of teaching load did you carry during the time?
I imagine it varied from time to time between 24 and 42, but just for some idea of perspective, I have some idea of how many.
what your load was?
Well, it was at least twice to three times what I have here.
Anyway, there was no time given off for anything except when I taught a course in biology, it was usually a five-hour course.
There would be four
laboratory hours a week and three lecture hours a week and I would teach at least two courses at a time and sometimes three.
You probably had to change your own labs too, I think.
Oh yeah, I did all of the laboratory work, getting out specimens and everything of that kind.
No such thing as an assistant.
I didn't mind that.
I would rather do it.
I know that you left the school at 842 during the war.
Was that, was it because of the war that you left or?
Yeah sometime in the 30s, late 30s, the president called me in and he says you're our new ground school instructor.
I said, what do you mean, ground school instructor?
He says, the flying school that we have here for students.
You'll remember that before World War II, the country was engaged in developing as many pilots as we could.
and the government subsidized nearly every school in the United States, I guess, to teach people how to fly, students how to fly.
I've forgotten the name of that program, the Civilian Pilot Training Program.
That's the name of it.
And I didn't know a thing about it, of course.
He called me in, but he said that I was it because the man that we had had accepted a job with the government and would no longer be available.
I argued that I didn't know anything about it.
How could I do it?
He said, you go do it.
So I did.
I bought me a bunch of books and boned up on them and went up to Oklahoma City and took examinations and all of the ground school subjects that they needed, which was
Meteorology and aircraft, parachutes, navigation, aircraft engines.
I believe that's all.
No, civil air regulations.
These are the things I had to have in order to teach.
So I started teaching and keeping ahead of my students.
So I had all of these, I had a teacher's license.
When World War II broke out, I was licensed for all of those.
Not only that, by that time I was a pilot on my own and had a civilian pilot license and owned my own airplane.
So when World War II broke out, the Navy sent me a telegram asking me to help with the war effort, so I did.
Simple as that.
I taught navigation most of it.
I believe you taught that in both Norman in Oklahoma and in Dallas.
Yes, Dallas Naval Air Station.
That's just west of Dallas, actually, at Grand Prairie.
And then later they moved me up to Oklahoma at Norman.
This I liked because I knew most of the people at the University of Oklahoma at Norman, and I set up a liaison with them.
By the time I got up there, I was hankering to get back to biology.
Well, they gave me a research room on the campus and all the microscopes and whatever I wanted to do a little research on the site.
And that's what I did.
No official connections or anything, but I worked with them.

After that, somewhere I believe in 1944, we got to the place where we had enough Navy instructors standing around doing nothing that I felt like I could turn the job over to somebody else and go back to biology.
Dr. Weiss at that time
Dean of the Graduate School at Norman, University of Oklahoma, called me one day and said he had a research job for me.
He said, I want to take it.
So I went to see him and it happened to be a job with the College of William & Mary and the Virginia Fisheries.
department.
These two were working together and running a laboratory at Yorktown.
The job was a study of the rib muscles on the seaside of Virginia.
The man who had been doing this job, Dr. Moore, got a job at New Hampshire, I believe.
and I took his place to finish up a project that had already begun.
Is this Ribbed Muscle?
Ribbed, R-I-B-B-E-D, Ribbed Muscle Modulus Domicilis.
It's a very common one all around the country.
He might be interested in what they were doing with these things.
During World War II,
We lost our source of chicken feed and vitamins, especially fortified chicken feed.
The Delmarva Peninsula, that's their big business, still is today, is raising chickens.
But they got all of their vitamins from the Japs.
Of course, we weren't speaking to the Japs at about that time.
So they were looking for another source and they found it in these mussels.
And the efforts were to culture this mussel in sufficient quantities to fill this need.
In other words, I was still in the war effort to some extent, but actually working for the College of William & Mary, supported by Dow Chemical Company.
Were you successful in cultivating the mussels?
No, we never did figure out a way to culture the mussels or to speed up their development at all.
That was being done by then with oysters, wasn't it?
Or has that been a more recent development?
The oysters, I don't think oysters have ever been used for vitamins.
What I mean, what I think commonly called oyster farming, were they not doing that with oysters?
Oh, farming oysters, yes.
When I finished this project, which took me only through that first letter about nine months, I joined the...
the College of William & Mary and the Virginia Fisher's Laboratory in the capacity of Director of Oyster Research.
In other words, I just moved from Waxapraga on the seaside over to Yorktown and continued working with them for about another year.
in the oyster culture area.
This is where I was introduced to oysters, but all these mussels and the oyster reefs were all together.
That year, with the mussels study, I lived in an old house right out on the edge of the water, and clear out of sight of everything.
And I spent the entire winter in the field.
That's all I did.
I hardly ever inside at all.

What spurred on my original question was I was wondering, maybe I'm mistaken in equating, not truly equating, but almost equating the technique that you would use with an oyster as opposed to one with a mussel.
And I was wondering why oysters could be cultivated and not mussels.

They have, I think, possibly the same problems, the disease problem, I think, as far as the muscles are concerned, but I don't know that because I never did actually get to study the muscles so far as their diseases were concerned.
I didn't study the oysters either as long as I was at...
at the Virginia Fisher's Laboratory, studying culture methods using the time-honored methods actually built up by the oyster, more than anything else, and attempting to improve on their methods.
so I got my introduction anyway to oyster biology and oyster culture methods at the College of William & Mary.
